SIMPLE: pretension
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pretension
<hw>Pre*ten"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧tention</ets>. See <er>Pretend</er>,
<er>Tension</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of pretending, or
laying claim; the act of asserting right or title.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The arrogant <qex>pretensions</qex> of Glengarry contributed to
protract the discussion.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A claim made, whether true or false; a right alleged
or assumed; a holding out the appearance of possessing a certain
character; <as>as, <ex>pretensions</ex> to scholarship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This was but an invention and <qex>pretension</qex> given out by
the Spaniards.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men indulge those opinions and practices that favor their
<qex>pretensions</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pretentative</ent>⟦br⟧
